            <div n="1">
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Great Mass of Native Gold.</hi>
                </head>
                <p>&#x2014;The auriferous allu-<lb break="no"/>via of Tzarevo-Nikolaefsk and
                        Tzarevo-Alexan-<lb break="no"/>drofsk, which had already furnished a product
                        of<lb break="yes"/>400 poods (the pood is 36 lbs. avoirdupois,
                        Kelly&#x2019;s<lb break="yes"/>
                    <hi rendition="#i">Cambist,</hi> i., 371), seemed nearly exhausted in 1837.<lb
                        break="yes"/>New researches were commenced in the neighbour-<lb break="no"
                    />hood, especially near the rivulet Tachkou-Targanka,<lb break="yes"/>which soon
                    gave rise to the discovery of a bed of<lb break="yes"/>auriferous sand, of a
                    very rich nature, but very<lb break="yes"/>limited in extent. This bed being
                    soon worked out,<lb break="yes"/>the waters of a pond, which had served for
                        washing<lb break="yes"/>the sands, were let off, and its bottom was
                        explored.<lb break="yes"/>Here was discovered an alluvium of more than 8<lb
                        break="yes"/>zolotniks (1 zolotnik = 65&#x215D; grains) in 100 poods.<lb
                        break="yes"/>All the valley of Tachkou-Targanka was now ex-<lb break="no"
                    />plored, except the spot on which stood the workshops<lb break="yes"/>for
                    washing the sand. In 1842 it was resolved to<lb break="yes"/>destroy these
                    shops, and after having washed the<lb break="yes"/>soil (of prodigious richness,
                    containing, in a small<lb break="yes"/>compass, 70 zolotniks per 100 poods of
                    sand), there was<lb break="yes"/>discovered on the 7th of November, under the
                        very<lb break="yes"/>corner of the building, at three metres (10 feet)
                        depth,<lb break="yes"/>resting upon a stratum of diorite, the monster
                        lump,<lb break="yes"/>weighing two poods 7 Russian pounds, and 92 zolot-<lb
                        break="no"/>niks (79 lbs. 1625 dec.). This mass has an undu-<lb break="no"
                    />lated surface; it is somewhat porous, and free from<lb break="yes"/>all trace
                    of matrix or gangue. The largest lump of<lb break="yes"/>native platina hitherto
                    found in the platiniferous<lb break="yes"/>alluvia of Nijni-Taguilsk weighs 20
                    Russian pounds<lb break="yes"/>and 34 zolotniks (= 18&#x00B7;319
                        lbs.)&#x2014;<hi rendition="#i">Humboldt&#x2019;s Asie<lb break="yes"
                        />Centrale.</hi>
                </p>
            </div>
